  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Application: Hydrostatic pressure on a circular drum
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Make substitutions based on the following:
      </p>

      <p>
        <tabular>
          <col halign="center" right="minor" /> <col halign="center" />
          <row>
            <cell>When you see...</cell>
            <cell>Substitute...</cell>
          </row>

          <row />
            <row>
              <cell> <m>a^{2}-x^{2}</m> </cell>
              <cell> <m>x=a\sin\theta</m> </cell>
            </row>

            <row>
              <cell> <m>x^{2}+a^{2}</m> </cell>
              <cell> <m>x=a\tan\theta</m> </cell>
            </row>

            <row>
              <cell> <m>x^{2}-a^{2}</m> </cell>
              <cell> <m>x=a\sec\theta</m> </cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          With definite integrals:
          <aside>
            <p>
              According to <em>Advanced Calculus</em> by James J. Callahan, this is a pullback substitution!
            </p>
          </aside>
        </p>

        <p>
          <me>
            \int_{a}^{b} f(x)\dd{x}=\int_{g\inv(a)}^{g\inv(b)}f(g(\theta))g'(\theta)\dd{\theta}
          </me>
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          From this we can get some basic derivatives of inverse trigonometric functions:
        </p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\dv{x}\Sin\inv(x) \amp = \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^{2}}} </mrow>
          <mrow>\dv{x}\Tan\inv(x) \amp = \frac{1}{1+x^{2}} </mrow>
          <mrow>\dv{x}\Sec\inv(x) \amp = \frac{1}{|x|\sqrt{x^2-1}} </mrow>
        </md>
      </li>
    </ul>
</section>
